      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i'm also seeing some weird behavior where the memory usage just keeps climbing even after i finish a loop. like it's not being released properly. is that just how garbage collection works in python or am i looking at a leak?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That climbing memory usage after a loop finishes, even when you think you're done, is often a classic sign of Python's garbage collector being a bit slow, or sometimes, it's just the way Python manages references. It's not always a true \"leak\" in the C sense, but it can feel like one when you're dealing with massive data structures.\n\nIf you're using generators, make sure you are actually consuming the generator fully. If you create a generator but never iterate through it—or if you store the entire generator object in a list without consuming it—that object itself can hold onto references, preventing the memory from being freed. Try to iterate over the generator completely, or explicitly clear any large variables you are holding onto.",
      "source": "target",
